          "body": "Verses 17-19 are the chapter's most theologically demanding. 'If a person sins and does any of the things which the LORD has commanded not to be done, though he was unaware, still he is guilty and shall bear his punishment.' The closing declaration drives the point home with emphatic Hebrew syntax: 'he was certainly guilty before the LORD' (asham asham — the doubled root). John Calvin, commenting on this class of cases, noted that God's law operates with a standard that transcends the sinner's subjective state of awareness. The human conscience is not the final moral arbiter; God's revealed will is. This is not cruelty — it is the only framework within which the gospel makes sense. If guilt were merely subjective, the cross would be unnecessary for anyone who feels no guilt. Because guilt is objective — a real condition before a real God regardless of felt awareness — the provision of atonement is universally necessary and, in Christ, universally available."
